#! /usr/local/bin/xs -c slider $*

This is a sample presentation using slider.

.h Demo of slider
.s Preliminaries
.i 2
.p The keys
.pb h
.c ,
.pb j
.c ,
.pb n
.c ,
.pd space
.c ,
.pd tab
.p and
.pd enter
.p advance to the next slide.
.
.i 4
.p The keys
.pb k
.c ,
.pb l
.c ,
.pb p
.c ,
.pd backspace
.c ,
.pd del
.p and
.pb `
.p return to the previous slide.
.
.i 6
.p The keys
.pb q
.p and
.pb .
.p terminate the program.
.f ... you know what to do, right?
.^

.s First slide
.f Saturday, April 28th 2018
.i 5
.p This is a
.pb bunch
.p of text.
.p It'll
.ph all
.pd show up
.p as one paragraph.
.p Also, it
.pi should
.p be long enough to
.pu wrap
.c .
.pd (At least it should in a typical 80-ish column terminal.)
.
.p This is another paragraph.
.pR We have a
.pG few of
.pY the colors
.pB of
.pM the
.pC rainbow
.c .
.
.i 10
.bh Here's a table
.bb   aaa  bbb  ccc
.bp     1   ax  3.0
.bp     2    z    7
.bp
.bd   ^ empty line
.bp   -    -    -
.^

.s Second slide
.p Here we are, then...
.
.i 41
.w 60
.pi BTW, I'm sorry for the fruit-salad. It's meant to
.pi exercise all of the formatters.
.i 20
.pb Tasteful slides don't do that.
.^

.s Third slide
.i 5
.p Can we go back?
.
.p (You do remember how to go back, right...?)
.
.v 20
.p If you have a "short" screen, this paragraph (or its tail) will silently
.p disappear; the footer will remain at its usual position and
.p the header will not scroll off the screen.)

.i 0
.p In the event of truncation, a dot will appear at the left of the page
.p number box on the last displayed line.
.^

.s Fourth slide
.w 40
.p Here's a paragraph on a narrow line. It should wrap.
.
.w 80
.i 40
.p Here's a paragraph with a large indent. It should also wrap.
.^

.s Fifth slide
.w 60
.i 5
.j 3
.p 1. We can do bullet items, too.
.
.p 2. Just write each point as a new paragraph;
.p use whatever marker you like, or none.
.
.p 3. The hanging indent is specified using the .j request.
.^

.s Last slide
.f Thanks!
.w 50
.i 32
.j 3
.v 3
.p This is the end, my friend.
.
.v 4
.i 24
